Poets insist you don't need to read any literary analyses to understand their poem, as long as you've read it, you will receive it as it was meant to be received. Abstract painters similarly say the immediacy of the art means you "get it" without having to read or study anything.

Experts in any artistic medium love to insist on its self-sufficiency, e.g. film directors when asked what one needs to read to "get" their film always tend to just respond that if you watched the film you successfully fully experienced it, it's about moving images on a screen...

To me this seems like something that is true retroactively, as in after one studies, reads film theory or literary analyses, etc. he finally realizes he never needed any of it to appreciate the poem or the image on the screen or the painting. Severian and the Claw sort of deal...

Salvador Dali often comes off as a wonderful cliche of himself, e.g. he has a quote about how good wine needs to come from vines grown by a madman, it's word for word what you would expect him to have said. Yet in spite of it somehow you are also very glad he did actually say it.
